export const missionContent = {
  eyebrow: 'Missions',
  title: 'Partnership-first ministry, shaped by what local churches in Scotland actually need.',
  paragraphs: [
    'The most frequently asked question we get is, "What do ya\'ll do in Scotland?" The short answer is that we host and facilitate missions for both our U.S. and Scottish partners. But the reality is that what we do in Scotland is quite complex.',
    'Depending on the research you trust, Scotland is somewhere between 1-5% evangelical Christian. Once known as the "land of the book," Scotland sent out more missionaries than any other country in the world only a few generations ago. Today there is still a strong community of true believers there, and part of this work is coming alongside them with encouragement, support, and partnership.',
    'We can offer to come alongside them. To partner with them. To listen to what they need and get a sense of what God is calling them to do for their own country. And when they ask, we can offer our services, resources, expertise, and experience. As the body of Christ, we can help shoulder the burdens of a post-Christian society.',
    'The two main ways we serve Scotland are through partnerships with local Scottish churches and mission trips with American church partners. Rebecca has developed a framework to help bridge the gap between the needs requested by Scottish church partners and the resources offered by their American counterparts through detailed church profiles and partnership matching.',
    'Early on in the process, we knew we were being led to have an impact locally within the community we would call home. We also knew we were being asked to serve outside of that community, in other areas, to help local churches spread the good news of Jesus Christ.',
    'That varies from church to church. The needs are great and can include leadership development, internships, student ministry, evangelism and outreach, pastoral care, discipleship, apologetics, facilities maintenance, and church planting.',
    "There's undeniable mutual benefit to U.S. churches in this reciprocal relationship as well. Scotland's churches model many things incredibly well, and their faithfulness is part of what makes this partnership meaningful in both directions.",
    'Mission teams play a vital role in the process. When a particular need in Scotland has been identified, teams spend seven days on the ground working alongside Scottish partners. As the host partner, we take care of every detail from the moment they land in Scotland until their final airport drop-off, with the Red Lion Inn serving as home base for many teams.',
    'There are other areas that we are exploring for ministry as well. The Lord has opened so many doors that it has truly blown us away, and we will continue to hold on loosely to the ideas He has given us as we seek to navigate His plan and His call to share the good news of Jesus with everyone we meet.',
  ],
  highlights: [
    'Local church partnerships',
    'Mission team logistics',
    'Reciprocal U.S. and Scottish support',
    'Leadership development and discipleship',
    'Church planting as the long-term aim',
  ],
  invitationTitle: 'Come Join Us',
  invitationBody: [
    "If your church or group is interested in sharing the good news, we'd like to pair your gifts and talent with the needs in Scotland. Scotland is rich in spiritual history, so your team might benefit from prayer walks or leadership training.",
    "Whatever your missionary calling is, we can design and develop a trip for you and your team. Missionary opportunities may include evangelism, creative arts, Bible teaching, working with children and students, working events, construction, community outreach, discipleship, and group training. We are currently connected with several local churches and organizations throughout the Edinburgh and Stirling areas.",
  ],
}

